he Political Economy of Inequality: Political Context and the Way Forward -- tCHAPTER 10 The Economic Discourse on Income Inequality -- tCHAPTER 11 Redistribution and Social Exclusion in the United States and Germany -- tCHAPTER 12 A Race-Conscious Economic Rights Approach to Providing Economic Security For All -- tCHAPTER 13 Law and the Collective Struggle for Economic Justice -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInequality of income and wealth has skyrocketed since the 1970s. As the super-rich have grasped the vast majority of the gains from economic growth, labor’s share of income has declined. The middle class has stagnated, and those at the bottom have become even worse off. Persistent structural discrimination on the basis of race and gender exacerbates these economic disparities.The Great Polarization brings together scholars from disparate fields to examine the causes and consequences of this dramatic rise in inequality. Contributors demonstrate that institutions, norms, policy, and political power—not the “natural” operation of the market—determine the distribution of wealth and income. The book underscores the role of ideas and ideologies, showing how neoclassical economics and related beliefs have functioned in public debates to justify inequality. Together, these essays bear out an inescapable conclusion: inequality is a choice. The rules of the economy have been rewritten to favor those at the top, entrenching the imbalances of power that widen the gap between the very rich and everyone else.Contributors reconsider the data on inequality, examine the policies that have led to this predicament, and outline potential ways forward. Using both theoretical and empirical analysis and drawing on the knowledge of experts in policy, political economy, economics, and other disciplines, The Great Polarization offers a kaleidoscopic view of the processes that have shaped today’s stark hierarchies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aIncome distributionzUnited States. 0aPolarization (Social sciences)zUnited States. 0aSocial stratificationzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Capitalism.2bisacsh1 aArnim, Rudiger L. von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnim, Rudiger von, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaker, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrales-Ruiz, Jose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraunstein, Elissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrain, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuménil, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErtürk, Korkut A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Darrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Eunice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevien, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLévy, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaloney, Thomas N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta-Muñoz, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMishel, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOcampo, José Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtt, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParet, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRada, Codrin